The atmospheric composition (and other conditions) should be prescribed as in the historical run (expt. 3.2) and the RCP 4.5 scenario (expt. 4.1) of the long term suite of experiments.

C4MIP style experiment to further understand "slower" carbon cycle responses (ie. feedbacks). Models with coupled carbon cycles would carry out one of two options with prescribed atmospheric [CO2].
1) * Initialize from 3.1::Control at the same point as 6.1::1%/yrCO2 * Impose conditions identical to 3.1::Control * but radiation code sees CO2 concentration increase at a rate of 1% per year as in 6.1 * run for 140 years
2) * Initialize from 3.1::Control at the same point as 3.2::20C * carbon cycle sees CO2 concentrations identical to 3.1::Control * All other model components impose conditions identical to > historical 3.2::20C > future 4.2::RCP8.5 * run for 251 years
Forced in this way, the carbon cycle (which sees control atmospheric CO2 concentration) responds to climate change alone.
For both options, the radiation code sees the same constant CO2 concentration as thin the control run (and in option 2 all other forcing is also omitted). Thus there is little climate change and the carbon cycle only responds to the CO2 increase.

C4MIP style experiment to diagnose the strength of "slower" carbon cycle responses (ie. feedbacks). Models with coupled carbon cycles would carry out one of two options with prescribed atmospheric [CO2]
1) * Initialize from 3.1::Control at the same point as 6.1::1%/yrCO2 * Impose conditions identical to 3.1::Control * but carbon cycle sees CO2 concentration increase at a rate of 1% per year as in 6.1 * run for 140 years
2) * Initialize from 3.1::Control at the same point as 3.2::20C * Impose conditions identical to 3.1::Control * but carbon cycle sees CO2 concentrations identical to > historical 3.2::20C > future 4.2::RCP8.5 * run for 251 years
For both options, the radiation code sees the same constant CO2 concentration as thin the control run (and in option 2 all other forcing is also omitted). Thus there is little climate change and the carbon cycle only responds to the CO2 increase.

Since there is at present no generally accepted "best" way to initialize models, some groups may choose to try different initialization methods.
For example, a repeat of runs in expt 1.1 using an alternative initialisation strategy or alternative initial data
